# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: detonation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:detonation/acetylene] As an alkyne, acetylene is unsaturated because its two carbon atoms are bonded together in a triple bond.
[src:detonation/acetylene] The carbon–carbon triple bond places all four atoms in the same straight line, with CCH bond angles of 180°.
[src:detonation/acetylene] The triple bond in acetylene results in a high energy content that is released when acetylene is burned.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Acetylene was discovered in 1836 by Edmund Davy, who identified it as a "new carburet of hydrogen".
[src:detonation/acetylene] It was an accidental discovery while attempting to isolate potassium metal.
[src:detonation/acetylene] By heating potassium carbonate with carbon at very high temperatures, he produced a residue of what is now known as potassium carbide, (K2C2), which reacted with water to release the new gas.
[src:detonation/acetylene] It was rediscovered in 1860 by French chemist Marcellin Berthelot, who coined the name *acétylène*.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Berthelot's empirical formula for acetylene (C4H2), as well as the alternative name "*quadricarbure d'hydrogène*" (hydrogen quadricarbide), were incorrect because many chemists at that time used the wrong atomic mass for carbon (6 instead of 12).
[src:detonation/acetylene] Berthelot was able to prepare this gas by passing vapours of organic compounds (methanol, ethanol, etc.) through a red hot tube and collecting the effluent.
[src:detonation/acetylene] He also found that acetylene was formed by sparking electricity through mixed cyanogen and hydrogen gases.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Berthelot later obtained acetylene directly by passing hydrogen between the poles of a carbon arc.
[src:detonation/acetylene] It is a recovered side product in production of ethylene by cracking of hydrocarbons.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Approximately 400,000 tonnes were produced by this method in 1983.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Its presence in ethylene is usually undesirable because of its explosive character and its ability to poison Ziegler–Natta catalysts.
[src:detonation/acetylene] It is selectively hydrogenated into ethylene, usually using Pd–Ag catalysts.
[src:detonation/acetylene] This last reaction is implemented in the process of anaerobic decomposition of methane by microwave plasma.
[src:detonation/acetylene] The first sample of acetylene produced was by Edmund Davy in 1836, via hydrolysis (decomposition using water) of potassium carbide.
[src:detonation/acetylene] This reaction was discovered by Friedrich Wöhler in 1862, but a suitable commercial scale production method which allowed acetylene to be put into wider scale use was not found until 1892 by the Canadian inventor Thomas Willson while searching for a viable commercial production method for aluminum.
[src:detonation/acetylene] As late as the early 21st century, China, Japan, and Eastern Europe produced acetylene primarily by this method.
[src:detonation/acetylene] The use of this technology has since declined worldwide with the notable exception of China, with its emphasis on coal-based chemical industry, as of 2013.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Otherwise oil has increasingly supplanted coal as the chief source of reduced carbon.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Calcium carbide production requires high temperatures, ~2000 °C, necessitating the use of an electric arc furnace.
[src:detonation/acetylene] In the US, this process was an important part of the late-19th century revolution in chemistry enabled by the massive hydroelectric power project at Niagara Falls.
[src:detonation/acetylene] In terms of valence bond theory, in each carbon atom the 2s orbital hybridizes with one 2p orbital thus forming an sp hybrid.
[src:detonation/acetylene] The other two 2p orbitals remain unhybridized.
[src:detonation/acetylene] The two ends of the two sp hybrid orbital overlap to form a strong σ valence bond between the carbons, while on each of the other two ends hydrogen atoms attach also by σ bonds.
[src:detonation/acetylene] The two unchanged 2p orbitals form a pair of weaker π bonds.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Since acetylene is a linear symmetrical molecule, it possesses the D∞h point group.
[src:detonation/acetylene] At atmospheric pressure, acetylene cannot exist as a liquid and does not have a melting point.
[src:detonation/acetylene] The triple point on the phase diagram corresponds to the melting point (−80.8 °C) at the minimal pressure at which liquid acetylene can exist (1.27 atm).
[src:detonation/acetylene] At temperatures below the triple point, solid acetylene can change directly to the vapour (gas) by sublimation.
[src:detonation/acetylene] The sublimation point at atmospheric pressure is −84.0 °C.
[src:detonation/acetylene] At room temperature and atmospheric pressure, the solubility of acetylene in acetone is 27.9 g per kg.
[src:detonation/acetylene] For the same amount of dimethylformamide (DMF), the solubility is 51 g.
[src:detonation/acetylene] At 20.26 bar, the solubility increases to 689.0 and 628.0 g for acetone and DMF, respectively.
[src:detonation/acetylene] These solvents are used in pressurized gas cylinders.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Approximately 20% of acetylene is supplied by the industrial gases industry for oxyacetylene gas welding and cutting due to the high temperature of the flame.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Combustion of acetylene with oxygen produces a flame of over 3,600 K (3,330 °C; 6,020 °F), releasing 11.8 kJ/g.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Oxygen with acetylene is the hottest burning common gas mixture.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Oxy-acetylene welding was a popular welding process in previous decades.
[src:detonation/acetylene] The development and advantages of arc-based welding processes have made oxy-fuel welding nearly extinct for many applications.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Acetylene usage for welding has dropped significantly.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Bell Canada cable-repair technicians still use portable acetylene-fuelled torch kits as a soldering tool for sealing lead sleeve splices in manholes and in some aerial locations.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Oxyacetylene welding may also be used in areas where electricity is not readily accessible.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Oxyacetylene cutting is used in many metal fabrication shops.
[src:detonation/acetylene] For use in welding and cutting, the working pressures must be controlled by a regulator, since above 15 psi (100 kPa), if subjected to a shockwave (caused, for example, by a flashback), acetylene decomposes explosively into hydrogen and carbon.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Acetylene is useful for many processes, but few are conducted on a commercial scale.
[src:detonation/acetylene] One of the major chemical applications is ethynylation of formaldehyde.
[src:detonation/acetylene] The reaction gives butynediol, with propargyl alcohol as the by-product.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Copper acetylide is used as the catalyst.
[src:detonation/acetylene] In addition to ethynylation, acetylene reacts with carbon monoxide to give acrylic acid, or acrylic esters.
[src:detonation/acetylene] These derivatives form products such as acrylic fibers, glasses, paints, resins, and polymers.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Except in China, use of acetylene as a chemical feedstock has declined by 70% from 1965 to 2007 owing to cost and environmental considerations.
[src:detonation/acetylene] In China, acetylene is a major precursor to vinyl chloride.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Prior to the widespread use of petrochemicals, coal-derived acetylene was a building block for several industrial chemicals.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Thus acetylene can be hydrated to give acetaldehyde, which in turn can be oxidized to acetic acid.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Processes leading to acrylates were also commercialized.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Almost all of these processes became obsolete with the availability of petroleum-derived ethylene and propylene.
[src:detonation/acetylene] In 1881, the Russian chemist Mikhail Kucherov described the hydration of acetylene to acetaldehyde using catalysts such as mercury(II) bromide.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Before the advent of the Wacker process, this reaction was conducted on an industrial scale.
[src:detonation/acetylene] The polymerization of acetylene with Ziegler–Natta catalysts produces polyacetylene films.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Polyacetylene, a chain of CH centres with alternating single and double bonds, was one of the first discovered organic semiconductors.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Its reaction with iodine produces a highly electrically conducting material.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Although such materials are not useful, these discoveries led to the developments of organic semiconductors, as recognized by the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 2000 to Alan J.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Heeger, Alan G MacDiarmid, and Hideki Shirakawa.
[src:detonation/acetylene] In the 1920s, pure acetylene was experimentally used as an inhalation anesthetic.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Acetylene is sometimes used for carburization (that is, hardening) of steel when the object is too large to fit into a furnace.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Acetylene is used to volatilize carbon in radiocarbon dating.
[src:detonation/acetylene] The carbonaceous material in an archeological sample is treated with lithium metal in a small specialized research furnace to form lithium carbide (also known as lithium acetylide).
[src:detonation/acetylene] The carbide can then be reacted with water, as usual, to form acetylene gas to feed into a mass spectrometer to measure the isotopic ratio of carbon-14 to carbon-12.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Acetylene combustion produces a strong, bright light and the ubiquity of carbide lamps drove much acetylene commercialization in the early 20th century.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Common applications included coastal lighthouses, street lights, and automobile and mining headlamps.
[src:detonation/acetylene] In most of these applications, direct combustion is a fire hazard, and so acetylene has been replaced, first by incandescent lighting and many years later by low-power/high-lumen LEDs.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Nevertheless, acetylene lamps remain in limited use in remote or otherwise inaccessible areas and in countries with a weak or unreliable central electric grid.
[src:detonation/acetylene] The energy richness of the C≡C triple bond and the rather high solubility of acetylene in water make it a suitable substrate for bacteria, provided an adequate source is available.
[src:detonation/acetylene] A number of bacteria living on acetylene have been identified.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Acetylene is a moderately common chemical in the universe, often associated with the atmospheres of gas giants.
[src:detonation/acetylene] One curious discovery of acetylene is on Enceladus, a moon of Saturn.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Natural acetylene is believed to form from catalytic decomposition of long-chain hydrocarbons at temperatures of 1,700 K (1,430 °C; 2,600 °F) and above.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Since such temperatures are highly unlikely on such a small distant body, this discovery is potentially suggestive of catalytic reactions within that moon, making it a promising site to search for prebiotic chemistry.
[src:detonation/acetylene] In vinylation reactions, H−X compounds add across the triple bond.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Alcohols and phenols add to acetylene to give vinyl ethers.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Similarly, vinylpyrrolidone and vinylcarbazole are produced industrially by vinylation of 2-pyrrolidone and carbazole.
[src:detonation/acetylene] The hydration of acetylene is a vinylation reaction, but the resulting vinyl alcohol isomerizes to acetaldehyde.
[src:detonation/acetylene] The reaction is catalyzed by mercury salts.
[src:detonation/acetylene] This reaction once was the dominant technology for acetaldehyde production, but it has been displaced by the Wacker process, which affords acetaldehyde by oxidation of ethylene, a cheaper feedstock.
[src:detonation/acetylene] A similar situation applies to the conversion of acetylene to the valuable vinyl chloride by hydrochlorination versus the oxychlorination of ethylene.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Vinyl acetate is used instead of acetylene for some vinylations, which are more accurately described as transvinylations.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Higher esters of vinyl acetate have been used in the synthesis of vinyl formate.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Acetylene and its derivatives (2-butyne, diphenylacetylene, etc.) form complexes with transition metals.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Its bonding to the metal is somewhat similar to that of ethylene complexes.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Metal acetylides, species of the formula L*n*M−C2R, are also common.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Copper(I) acetylide and silver acetylide can be formed in aqueous solutions with ease due to a favorable solubility equilibrium.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Various organometallic and inorganic reagents are effective.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Acetylene can be semihydrogenated to ethylene, providing a feedstock for a variety of polyethylene plastics.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Acetylene is not especially toxic, but when generated from calcium carbide, or CaC2, it can contain toxic impurities such as traces of phosphine and arsine, which gives it a distinct garlic-like smell.
[src:detonation/acetylene] It is also highly flammable, as are most light hydrocarbons, hence its use in welding.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Although it is stable at normal pressures and temperatures, if it is subjected to pressures as low as 15 psig it can explode.
[src:detonation/acetylene] The safe limit for acetylene therefore is 101 kPagage, or 15 psig.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Additionally, if acetylene is initiated by intense heat or a shockwave, it can decompose explosively if the absolute pressure of the gas exceeds about 200 kilopascals (29 psi).
[src:detonation/acetylene] It is therefore supplied and stored dissolved in acetone or dimethylformamide (DMF), contained in a gas cylinder with a porous filling, which renders it safe to transport and use, given proper handling.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Acetylene cylinders should be used in the upright position to avoid withdrawing acetone during use.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Information on safe storage of acetylene in upright cylinders is provided by the OSHA, Compressed Gas Association, United States Mine Safety and Health Administration (MSHA), EIGA, and other agencies.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Copper catalyses the decomposition of acetylene, and as a result acetylene should not be transported in copper pipes.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Cylinders should be stored in an area segregated from oxidizers to avoid exacerbated reaction in case of fire/leakage.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Acetylene cylinders should not be stored in confined spaces, enclosed vehicles, garages, and buildings, to avoid unintended leakage leading to explosive atmosphere.
[src:detonation/acetylene] In the US, National Electric Code (NEC) requires consideration for hazardous areas including those where acetylene may be released during accidents or leaks.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Consideration may include electrical classification and use of listed Group A electrical components in US.
[src:detonation/acetylene] Further information on determining the areas requiring special consideration is in NFPA 497.
[src:detonation/acetylene] In Europe, ATEX also requires consideration for hazardous areas where flammable gases may be released during accidents or leaks.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] Manual fire suppression includes the use of a fire blanket, fire extinguisher, or a standpipe system.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] A fire blanket is a sheet of fire retardant material that is designed to be placed over a fire to smother it out.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] Small fire blankets are meant for inception stage fires.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] They are normally made of fiberglass or Kevlar.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] Larger ones can be found in laboratories and factories, and are designed to be wrapped around a person whose clothes have caught fire.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers are devices that contain and discharge a substance that extinguishes or puts out a fire.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] These handheld devices come in a huge range of sizes, but the most common are portable fire extinguishers, typically weighing up to 15 kg in total.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] These can be easily handled and operated by one person and placement can either be wall-mounted, on a fire extinguisher trolley or housed inside a cabinet.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers are one of the most common manual fire suppression devices and are required in all commercial buildings and vehicles.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers can be used with little to no training and are meant for small incipient stage fires.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] The most common extinguisher is the ABC extinguisher and are found in most offices and homes.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] It can be used on normal fires, liquid fires, and electrical fires.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] There are also special extinguishers for kitchen fires and for use on burning metals, those being Class K and Class D respectively.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] Standpipes are installed in most large, multistory buildings.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] There are two types of standpipes: dry and wet.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] Most standpipes are dry systems and cannot be used by the public.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] Dry systems require a fire engine to pump water into the system.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] Most dry systems do not have pre-connected hoses and require firefighters to bring in the hose.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] In wet systems, there is always water in the pipes and they can be used by anyone.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] Wet systems will have hoses so building occupants can try and extinguish fires.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] Wet systems are becoming less common with the increase in number of sprinkler systems being installed.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] In some systems, firefighters have the option of pumping a Fire Department Connection (FDC) which will increase the water pressure at a standpipe in the event of a fire pump failure or loss of pressure.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] Typically, these systems pressurize the sprinkler system or the standpipe but not both at the same time.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] Automatic control means are any form of suppression that requires no human intervention these can include a fire sprinkler system, a gaseous clean agent, or automatic foam suppression system.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] Most automatic suppression systems would be found in large commercial kitchens or other high-risk areas.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] Fire sprinkler systems are installed in all types of buildings, commercial and residential.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] They are usually located at ceiling level and are connected to a reliable water source, most commonly municipal water supply.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] A typical automatic sprinkler system operates when heat at the site of a fire causes a fusible link or glass component in the sprinkler head to fail, thereby releasing the water from the sprinkler head.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] This means that only the sprinkler heads at the fire location actuate – not all the sprinklers on a floor or in a building.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] However, certain systems, such as deluge systems, do spray water from all heads in the same zone upon actuation.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] Sprinkler systems help to reduce the growth of a fire, thereby increasing life safety and limiting structural damage.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] Gaseous clean agents are installed to result in less fire and water damage than sprinklers, such as in computer rooms.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] The system works by flooding an area with a gas which interferes with the fire tetrahedron.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] These systems are often found in areas where people are not going to be present when the system is activated such as datacenters, cooling systems, and other industrial applications.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] Activating a gaseous clean agent system when people are present can cause injury or death, and are usually equipped with an audible notification system to warn any potential occupants to evacuate the area.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] Automatic foam suppression systems come in three main forms low expansion, medium expansion, and high expansion.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] Low expansion foam expands less than 20 times its original size.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] These systems can be installed in a variety of places but are commonly found in places where hydrocarbons are stored.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] Low expansion foam systems when using film forming work by making a blanket of foam over the burning liquid to both cool it down and suppress the vapors.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] Medium expansion foam expands between 20 and 200 times its original size.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] These can be installed in outdoor settings like transfer stations or for use in open pits.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] Medium foam is used outdoors because it is denser than high expansion and will not blow away as easily.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] It works by covering what is on fire in a thick blanket of foam to smother it and suppress vapors.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] High expansion foam expands between 200 and 1000 times its original size.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] These systems are commonly installed in large volume areas like airplane hangars, mine shafts, and ship holds.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] These systems are normally installed inside and make a very light foam.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] They extinguish the fire by rapid smothering and cooling.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] Its rapid rate of expansion enables it to fill large areas with foam rapidly.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] When used on LNG tanks they provide an added insulation layer that helps reduce the vapor rate.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] Nozzles that are powered by electrical energy that is generated and supplied by fire detection and control devices and are typically closed.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] ILDFA uses a dual approach, combining a water-based fire suppression system in conjunction with a hollow, perforated flooring system to drain and remove spilled flammable liquid.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] This approach reduces the risk of pool fires inside infrastructure by diverting any leaked fuel away from potential ignition sources or by extinguishing any flammable liquid fire by depriving it of oxygen once it is removed.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] Fire detection works using smoke or heat sensors.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] These systems are very effective tool at alerting people in the immediate vicinity of where the fire is detected but building regulations require an integrated fire detection system.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] These system not only alerts people throughout the building by triggering the fire alarm but it can also summon emergency services.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] There are two types of systems available – addressable and conventional.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] Addressable systems monitor the specific location of each device (e.g. smoke detector, call point or sounder).
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] It means in the event of a fire or other emergency you know exactly where the problem is.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] This saves precious time and helps the emergency services prevent the loss of life and serious damage.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] Conventional systems can only determine the problem is in a general area and thus are more suited for small sites.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] When the fire detection system is activated it can also send an alert to the local fire department, broadcast a prerecorded warning message and unlock the buildings access control system.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] Hypoxic air fire prevention systems, also known as oxygen reduction systems are new automatic fire prevention systems that permanently reduce the oxygen concentration inside the protected volumes so that ignition or fire spreading cannot occur.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] Unlike traditional fire suppression systems that usually extinguish fire after it is detected, hypoxic air is able to prevent fires.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] At lower altitudes hypoxic air is safe to breathe for healthy individuals.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] All AFP systems are required to be installed and maintained in accordance with strict guidelines in order to maintain compliance with the local building code and the fire code.
[src:detonation/active-fire-protection] AFP works alongside modern architectural designs and construction materials and fire safety education to prevent, retard, and suppress structural fires.
[src:detonation/aleksandr-solomonovich-kompaneets] Kompaneyets was a student of Lev Landau in Kharkiv in the 1930s, where he dealt with solid state physics (electrical conductivity in metals and semiconductors).
[src:detonation/aleksandr-solomonovich-kompaneets] In 1936 he received his doctorate (candidate title) and habilitated in 1939 (Russian doctorate).
[src:detonation/aleksandr-solomonovich-kompaneets] He was a professor at the Institute of Chemical Physics at the Russian Academy of Sciences in Moscow (where he worked from 1946 until the end of his life) and is best known for his introductory textbook on theoretical physics.
[src:detonation/aleksandr-solomonovich-kompaneets] He also dealt with the physics of detonation, which he wrote about in a book with Yakov Zeldovich, and generally about gases at high temperatures.
[src:detonation/aleksandr-solomonovich-kompaneets] In the nuclear weapons program, he worked among others, Zeldovich since the 1940s (at the Institute of Chemical Physics), even at the theoretical examination (from 1948) of the early proposals (1946) of Zeldovich, Isaak Gurevich, Isaac Jakovlevic Pomeranchuk and Yulii Khariton on the hydrogen bomb.
[src:detonation/aleksandr-solomonovich-kompaneets] Kompaneyets dealt with many areas of theoretical physics, from chemical kinetics to biophysics.
[src:detonation/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] The **American Institute of Chemical Engineers** (**AIChE**) is a professional organization for chemical engineers.
[src:detonation/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] AIChE was established in 1908 to distinguish chemical engineers as professionals independent of chemists and mechanical engineers.
[src:detonation/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] By 2024, AIChE had over 60,000 members from over 110 countries (sources vary).
[src:detonation/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] There are over 350 active student chapters at universities worldwide.
[src:detonation/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Student chapters aim to provide networking opportunities in academia and industry as well as increase student involvement locally and nationally.
[src:detonation/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] This section consists of excerpts from a historical pamphlet written for the Silver Anniversary of the AICHE in 1932.
[src:detonation/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] In 1905, *The Chemical Engineer* rounded out its first year of publication with an editorial by its founder and prominent engineer, Richard K.
[src:detonation/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Meade, that propounded the question: "Why not the American Society of Chemical Engineers?" He went on to say: "The profession is now a recognized one and there are probably at least five hundred chemical engineers in this country".
[src:detonation/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] The mechanical, civil, electrical, and mining engineers in the United States each had already established a national society, so Meade's editorial was quite pertinent.
[src:detonation/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] But it took time for the idea to take root and Meade kept promoting it for the next two years.
[src:detonation/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Finally, in 1907, he issued a call for a preliminary meeting to be held in Atlantic City in June 1907.
[src:detonation/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Some early leaders of the profession, Charles F.
[src:detonation/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Sadtler, and Thorn Smith along with about a dozen others answered Meade's call and met in Atlantic City on June 21, 1907.
[src:detonation/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] The meeting concluded with the formation of an organizing committee of six members: Charles F.
[src:detonation/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] The organizing committee sent a letter in September 1908 to 600 men in the chemical profession in the United States and Canada asking for their opinions about forming a chemical engineering society.
[src:detonation/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Two hundred replies were received and 70-80% were favorable.
[src:detonation/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Many of the others believed the existing societies (especially the American Chemical Society) were sufficient and they did not favor forming a new society.
[src:detonation/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] The organizing committee decided to hold a larger, open meeting at the Hotel Belmont in New York City at which those opposed to forming the new society could present their arguments and opinions.
[src:detonation/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Accordingly, they invited fifty men prominent in the chemical profession (including men who opposed the forming of a new society) to meet on January 18, 1908.
[src:detonation/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Twenty-one men attended the meeting and fourteen others expressed their views in letters.
[src:detonation/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] After much discussion, the meeting ended without reaching a definitive decision.
[src:detonation/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] However, it was agreed to have a mail vote (on whether or not to form a chemical engineering society) after a complete stenographic report of the meeting was printed and sent to the fifty men who had been invited to the meeting.
[src:detonation/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] The mail vote resulted in 36 replies of which 22 were in the affirmative, 6 were negative, and 8 were neutral.
[src:detonation/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Based on those voting results, the organizing committee of six called for a full-fledged organizational meeting to be held in Philadelphia on June 22, 1908.
[src:detonation/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Meanwhile, the committee of six drafted a proposed constitution to be presented at that meeting.
[src:detonation/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] That meeting resulted in the official formation of the American Institute of Chemical Engineers, the adoption of a constitution, and the election of Samuel P.
[src:detonation/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Sadtler as the first president of the Institute.
[src:detonation/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Divisions and forums provide technical information, programming for AIChE's technical meetings, and awards and recognition to outstanding chemical engineers in their areas of expertise.
[src:detonation/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] They also provide opportunities for affiliation with top engineers in the general disciplines as well as in emerging fields like biotechnology and sustainability.
[src:detonation/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] The prerequisite qualifications for election to any of the membership grades are available in the AIChE Bylaws.
[src:detonation/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] As new technology is developed, there is a need for experts to collaborate to achieve common goals.
[src:detonation/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] AIChE plays a major role through joint initiatives with industry, academia, and others.
[src:detonation/area-of-refuge] An **area of refuge** or **safe room** is a place in a building designed to hold occupants during a fire or other emergency when evacuation may not be safe or possible.
[src:detonation/area-of-refuge] Occupants can wait there until rescued or relieved by firefighters.
[src:detonation/area-of-refuge] In some instances, an area of refuge or refuge area may refer to a designated space in a multi-unit residential building that can provide relief from unsafe or uncomfortable conditions in individual units.
[src:detonation/area-of-refuge] An area of refuge is typically supplied with a steady supply of fresh or filtered outside air.
[src:detonation/area-of-refuge] A two way communication system is provided on each floor above or below the main floor.
[src:detonation/area-of-refuge] A call box is required in each area of refuge, which can call into a central location called a base station.
[src:detonation/area-of-refuge] If the station is not attended 24 hours a day, the call must automatically call to an outside location and have two-way voice person to person communication capabilities.
[src:detonation/area-of-refuge] Such locations are usually required to be bounded by fire-resistant walls and floors.
[src:detonation/area-of-refuge] In the context of climate change, where older buildings may not be designed for changing climate conditions, refuge spaces are sometimes discussed in terms of providing communal areas in multi-unit buildings for when temperature and air quality is not safe or comfortable in individual units.
[src:detonation/arthur-b-guise-medal] Guise Medal** was established in 1983 and has been awarded annually starting in 1985 by the Society of Fire Protection Engineers.
[src:detonation/arthur-b-guise-medal] Named in memory of Arthur Guise, an engineer who developed dry chemicals as fire extinguishing agents, it recognizes eminent achievement in the advancement of the science and technology of fire protection engineering.
[src:detonation/aspirating-smoke-detector] An **aspirating smoke detector** (**ASD**) is a system used in active fire protection, consisting of a central detection unit which draws air through a network of pipes to detect smoke.
[src:detonation/aspirating-smoke-detector] The sampling chamber is based on a nephelometer that detects the presence of smoke particles suspended in air by detecting the light scattered by them in the chamber.
[src:detonation/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASDs can typically detect smoke before it is visible to the naked eye.
[src:detonation/aspirating-smoke-detector] In most cases aspirating smoke detectors require a fan unit to draw in a sample of air from the protected area through its network of pipes.
[src:detonation/aspirating-smoke-detector] In 1970 the Australian Commonwealth Scientific and Industrial Research Organisation (CSIRO) used a nephelometer to carry out research into forest fires.
[src:detonation/aspirating-smoke-detector] Subsequently, the Australian Postmaster-General's Department engaged the CSIRO to investigate technologies that could prevent service interruption due to fire.
[src:detonation/aspirating-smoke-detector] After selecting a sample site to carry out research, the CSIRO suggested that the nephelometer should be used as the benchmark for the APO fire tests.
[src:detonation/aspirating-smoke-detector] This was installed to monitor smoke levels within the return-air ducts of the mechanical ventilation system, utilising a chart-recorder output display.
[src:detonation/aspirating-smoke-detector] At the conclusion of several weeks of testing, it was discovered that there no commercially available fire detection technology suitable for preventing damage to telephone equipment.
[src:detonation/aspirating-smoke-detector] One technology that did show great promise however was the nephelometer itself.
[src:detonation/aspirating-smoke-detector] In 1979, Xtralis, then IEI Pty Ltd., produced and sold an air sampling device they called VESDA (Very Early Smoke Detection Apparatus).
[src:detonation/aspirating-smoke-detector] The company redesigned the detector in 1982 to provide the reliability, features, size and reduced cost for export markets.
[src:detonation/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD systems have gained popularity due to their ability to sense smoke long before a catastrophic incident.
[src:detonation/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD design corrects shortcomings of conventional smoke detectors by using a sampling pipe with multiple holes.
[src:detonation/aspirating-smoke-detector] The air samples are captured and filtered, removing any contaminants or dust to avoid false alarms and then processed by a centralized, highly sensitive laser detection unit.
[src:detonation/aspirating-smoke-detector] If smoke is detected, the systems alarm is triggered, and signals are then processed through centralized monitoring stations within a few seconds.
[src:detonation/aspirating-smoke-detector] Unlike passive smoke detection systems, including spot detectors, ASD systems actively draw smoke to the detector through bore holes within a piping system that runs throughout the protected area.
[src:detonation/aspirating-smoke-detector] Furthermore, ASD systems incorporate integrity monitoring to ensure an alert is raised at any time the ASD's ability to detect smoke is compromised.
[src:detonation/aspirating-smoke-detector] This is not the case with passive devices that are generally only electrically monitored with no ability to determine if smoke can actually reach the detection element.
[src:detonation/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD systems incorporate more than one level of alarm.
[src:detonation/aspirating-smoke-detector] This allows an ASD system to provide very early warning of an event, prompting investigation at the earliest smouldering stage of a fire when it is easily addressed.
[src:detonation/aspirating-smoke-detector] Other alarm levels may be configured to provide fire alarm inputs to fire systems as well as releasing suppression systems.
[src:detonation/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD alarm sensitivities are configurable and can be programmed to levels ranging from thousands of times more sensitive than a conventional detector, to much less sensitive.
[src:detonation/aspirating-smoke-detector] The detectors work best in non-volatile environments.
[src:detonation/aspirating-smoke-detector] They can also be used in computer cabinets to alert users to the overheating of computer cables or individual computer components.
[src:detonation/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASDs are suitable for environments where a highly sensitive rapid smoke detection capability is required.
[src:detonation/aspirating-smoke-detector] This makes them suitable in clean rooms; areas which contain goods easily damaged by fire, such as tobacco, electronic rooms and highly flammable liquid and gases.
[src:detonation/aspirating-smoke-detector] Often, normal point detectors will recognise the danger too late, as smoke often does not reach the ceiling quickly enough for a fire to be detected in a timely fashion.
[src:detonation/aspirating-smoke-detector] As they can be easily hidden, pipe networks are suitable in environments where point detectors can be considered aesthetically displeasing, such as offices, apartments and hotel rooms.
[src:detonation/aspirating-smoke-detector] This factor also makes them suitable in locations where point detectors can be easily tampered with, such as in correctional facilities.
[src:detonation/aspirating-smoke-detector] Despite their high sensitivity ASDs can be used in dusty or dirty environments as long as correct design, installation and maintenance processes are followed.
[src:detonation/aspirating-smoke-detector] Most ASD products can accommodate a broad range of environments and applications – from both confined and open spaces to the cleanest or dirtiest environment, including telecomm, control rooms, waste treatment, mining and more.
[src:detonation/detonation] Detonations occur in both conventional solid and liquid explosives, as well as in reactive gases.
[src:detonation/detonation] TNT, dynamite, and C4 are examples of high power explosives that detonate.
[src:detonation/detonation] The velocity of detonation in solid and liquid explosives is much higher than that in gaseous ones, which allows the wave system to be observed with greater detail (higher resolution).
[src:detonation/detonation] A very wide variety of fuels may occur as gases (e.g. hydrogen), droplet fogs, or dust suspensions.
[src:detonation/detonation] In addition to dioxygen, oxidants can include halogen compounds, ozone, hydrogen peroxide, and oxides of nitrogen.
[src:detonation/detonation] Gaseous detonations are often associated with a mixture of fuel and oxidant in a composition somewhat below conventional flammability ratios.
[src:detonation/detonation] They happen most often in confined systems, but they sometimes occur in large vapor clouds.
[src:detonation/detonation] Other materials, such as acetylene, ozone, and hydrogen peroxide, are detonable in the absence of an oxidant (or reductant).
[src:detonation/detonation] In these cases the energy released results from the rearrangement of the molecular constituents of the material.
[src:detonation/detonation] Detonation was discovered in 1881 by four French scientists Marcellin Berthelot and Paul Marie Eugène Vieille and Ernest-François Mallard and Henry Louis Le Chatelier.
[src:detonation/detonation] The mathematical predictions of propagation were carried out first by David Chapman in 1899 and by Émile Jouguet in 1905, 1906 and 1917.
[src:detonation/detonation] The next advance in understanding detonation was made by John von Neumann and Werner Döring in the early 1940s and Yakov B.
[src:detonation/detonation] Zel'dovich and Aleksandr Solomonovich Kompaneets in the 1960s.
[src:detonation/detonation] The simplest theory to predict the behaviour of detonations in gases is known as the Chapman–Jouguet (CJ) condition, developed around the turn of the 20th century.
[src:detonation/detonation] This theory, described by a relatively simple set of algebraic equations, models the detonation as a propagating shock wave accompanied by exothermic heat release.
[src:detonation/detonation] Such a theory describes the chemistry and diffusive transport processes as occurring abruptly as the shock passes.
[src:detonation/detonation] A more complex theory was advanced during World War II independently by Zel'dovich, von Neumann, and Döring.
[src:detonation/detonation] This theory, now known as ZND theory, admits finite-rate chemical reactions and thus describes a detonation as an infinitesimally thin shock wave, followed by a zone of exothermic chemical reaction.
[src:detonation/detonation] With a reference frame of a stationary shock, the following flow is subsonic, so that an acoustic reaction zone follows immediately behind the lead front, the Chapman–Jouguet condition.
[src:detonation/detonation] There is also some evidence that the reaction zone is semi-metallic in some explosives.
[src:detonation/detonation] Both theories describe one-dimensional and steady wavefronts.
[src:detonation/detonation] However, in the 1960s, experiments revealed that gas-phase detonations were most often characterized by unsteady, three-dimensional structures, which can only, in an averaged sense, be predicted by one-dimensional steady theories.
[src:detonation/detonation] Indeed, such waves are quenched as their structure is destroyed.
[src:detonation/detonation] The Wood-Kirkwood detonation theory can correct some of these limitations.
[src:detonation/detonation] Experimental studies have revealed some of the conditions needed for the propagation of such fronts.
[src:detonation/detonation] In confinement, the range of composition of mixes of fuel and oxidant and self-decomposing substances with inerts are slightly below the flammability limits and, for spherically expanding fronts, well below them.
[src:detonation/detonation] The influence of increasing the concentration of diluent on expanding individual detonation cells has been elegantly demonstrated.
[src:detonation/detonation] Similarly, their size grows as the initial pressure falls.
[src:detonation/detonation] Since cell widths must be matched with minimum dimension of containment, any wave overdriven by the initiator will be quenched.
[src:detonation/detonation] Mathematical modeling has steadily advanced to predicting the complex flow fields behind shocks inducing reactions.
[src:detonation/detonation] To date, none has adequately described how the structure is formed and sustained behind unconfined waves.
[src:detonation/detonation] When used in explosive devices, the main cause of damage from a detonation is the supersonic blast front (a powerful shock wave) in the surrounding area.
[src:detonation/detonation] This is a significant distinction from deflagrations where the exothermic wave is subsonic and maximum pressures for non-metal specks of dust are approximately 7–10 times atmospheric pressure.
[src:detonation/detonation] Therefore, detonation is a feature for destructive purposes while deflagration is favored for the acceleration of firearms' projectiles.
[src:detonation/detonation] However, detonation waves may also be used for less destructive purposes, including deposition of coatings to a surface or cleaning of equipment (e.g. slag removal) and even explosively welding together metals that would otherwise fail to fuse.
[src:detonation/detonation] Pulse detonation engines use the detonation wave for aerospace propulsion.
[src:detonation/detonation] The first flight of an aircraft powered by a pulse detonation engine took place at the Mojave Air & Space Port on January 31, 2008.
[src:detonation/detonation] Unintentional detonation when deflagration is desired is a problem in some devices.
[src:detonation/detonation] In Otto cycle, or gasoline engines it is called engine knocking or pinging, and it causes a loss of power.
[src:detonation/detonation] It can also cause excessive heating, and harsh mechanical shock that can result in eventual engine failure.
[src:detonation/detonation] In firearms, it may cause catastrophic and potentially lethal failure.
[src:detonation/detonation] Pulse detonation engines are a form of pulsed jet engine that has been experimented with on several occasions as this offers the potential for good fuel efficiency.
